  "summary": "After the elderly man who assisted her earlier departs, Mrs. Barnes arrives to offer Joyce tea and comfort, suggesting that Joyce's fiancé, Arthur Harley, will provide a new dog if Trey does not recover. However, Joyce receives a phone call informing her that Trey has died alone.\n\nWhen Arthur arrives to take Joyce away from her home, she rejects his offer of marriage and financial stability. She reveals that her only motive for marrying him was to ensure she could keep Trey, and she expresses deep hatred for Arthur, describing him as a cruel person who enjoys hurting others. After Joyce rejects him, an angry Arthur leaves.\n\nFeeling numb and contemplating suicide, Joyce visits an employment agency. Mrs. Lambert informs her that no local daytime jobs are available, leading Joyce to consider working abroad. During an interview with Mr. Alabi, who offers her a position caring for his elderly aunt and his three-year-old son, Joyce realizes that he is the same gentleman who helped her with Trey earlier. Mr. Alabi shares that he also lost a dog two years ago, creating a moment of emotional connection. Joyce accepts the job and signs the necessary documents. Upon her return home, Mrs. Barnes informs Joyce that Trey's body has been delivered and that she will dig a pit in the backyard to bury the dog.",
